Introduction ¶

Source of Dataset

This dataset named New York City Airbnb Open data was sourced from Kaggle.com. The dataset contains prices of Airbnb listings within New York City, America, and other relevant information of each listing. The dataset comprises listing activity and its respective metrics in New York City in 2019.

Data Details and Information

The New York City Airbnb Open Data is about the listings on Airbnb in New York City in the Year 2019. The dataset itself was originally provided by Airbnb. The dataset contains information about the price per night of listings, locations (neighborhoods & latitude or longitude), names of listings, and their host. Furthermore, it also contains a minimum night of stay for each listing, the type of property of each listing, the number of reviews of each listing, the number of listings from the host over 365 Days, and listing availability over 365 Days. The datasets comprises enough data to conduct regression modelling to predict New York Airbnb prices based on different factors.

Within The New York City Airbnb Open Data, we have identified several features that are not relevant to our analysis and as a result will be dropping them from the dataset

The dataset contains a total of 48,895 Observations and 16 features.

Target Feature¶

The target feature for the dataset on Airbnb listings is the price. We aim to predict the price of Airbnb listings based on external factors and descriptive features.

Goals & Objectives ¶

New York, the most expensive city in the U.S is a massive tourist attraction. Attracting many tourists from around the globe, travelers intending to stay in New York City can find tens of thousands of listings on Airbnb for vacation rentals. We want to explore the impact factors like location has on the price of rentals. By identifying patterns that can be used as indicators to determine the cost of vacation rentals, we can gain a better understanding of what gives worth to the different locations of housing, and formulate theories on why tourists are attracted to such places.

These patterns can give us insights into how demand in the housing market is determined, or whether certain tourist attraction's popularity affects or is affected by the rentals. Then we can narrow down the biggest contributing factors to the worth of these rentals and locations. We can accomplish this through insightful data analysis and disaggregation and in the next phase, through predictive modelling. The aim is to derive something meaningful through visualisations of the data, exploration of how different factors can influence each other, and discover what patterns indicate certain results.

Such a statistical model that would predict the prices of Airbnb listings would serve to the advantage of travelers or any person considering to use hotels. The model would also be beneficial for economists who want to determine the indicators of housing market health. Banks may also benefit by being able to assess the financial prospects of mortgages they offer.

In [8]:
df = df.dropna()

Missing values were only found within the reviews_per_month column. We decided to drop all rows contaning missing values, as values with missing values within the reviews_per_month column will also contain 0 reviews. Therefore, it wouldn't make sense to impute for these missing values and also due to the context of the dataset it could potentially lead to an inaccurate representation of each listing and also because we could potentially intoduce bias from imputation

Furthermore, the reason the null values in reviews_per_month is being dropped is because the dataset source hasn't given any explanation for why the null values exist, so it would be safer to drop all the rows with null values as we want to preserve the integrity of the data. This won't result in bias because existence of this value does not depend on any other feature, and there is no pattern or cause to the null values.

To check for outliers within the dataset, using the .describe() function will be applied to populate summary stastics. Outliers were identifed within this dataset.

Upon analysis, the price_per_night does contain outliers. This could be because of bad data, wrong user input or is deliberate and geninune. Treating the price_per_night variable is essential to remove any potential skewness and any siginfiance to the price_per_night variable.

Furthermore, calculated_host_listings_counts contained outliers, this could simply be because of bad data, wrong user input and or is deliberate or geninue, but treating the outliers ensures that no unncessary potential skweness is introduced within the data and for further data visulisations

As you may see that minimum_nights_to_book, number_of_reviews and reviews_per_month also contained outliers. However, we decided not to treat these features for outliers because treating them for outliers does not make sense to the context of the dataset, because minimum nights to book can be high depending on the host's preferences and treating reviews for outliers could diminish the listings overall "value". Furthermore, to still recognise the potenital of bad data or input error data we filtered down the values in Minimum Nights to less than 366 days to ensure that any bad or input data is avidoed without dimnishing the overall value of a listing. Therefore, as it would result in an inaccurate representation of those respective features we did not treat them for outliers.

In [13]:
# Treating for Outliers for minimum_nights_to_book variable, calculated host_listings_count and price_per_night #

cols = ['calculated_host_listings_count', 'price_per_night'] # one or more

Q1 = df[cols].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df[cols].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

df_airbnb = df[~((df[cols] < (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)) |(df[cols] > (Q3 + 1.5 * IQR))).any(axis=1)]
df_airbnb = df_airbnb.loc[(df_airbnb['minimum_nights_to_book'] < 366)]


df_airbnb.describe() # Display Summary Statistics after removing outliers

Conclusions ¶

The predictive model of hotel prices from Airbnb has great applicability for those who either own hotels or are choosing hotels. This can allow for hotel owners to fine tune their prices to predictions based on the features of their listed properties or allow consumers/travelers to make more better calculated and reliable decisions based on their preferred attributes.

Our target feature for this project was price. We have illustrated a variety of factors that affect prices of Airbnb rentals. For phase 1, we cleaned the dataset from any useless features such as ID's, names, neighbourhood, last review, host details, longitude and latitude. We filtered out outliers from our dataset and removed all the null values as keeping them was problematic. We then sampled to 5000 instances.

We then visualized the data through various charts and illustrations to gain meaning and insights by comparing multiple variables with each other and making observations on them. We have gained insights into the availability of the listings, as well as the overall price of listings and of room types. We have found many variables that have a significant effect on price, such as the number of host listings, room types and the boroughs of listings.

Through our 3 variable plots, we have found how Manhattan in comparison to other boroughs have a higher minimum nights booking requirement, in addition to it being the most expensive borough. Other than this, we have found that many of our descriptive features have almost no effect on the price, such as availability, total reviews and reviews per month. Overall, we found that the borough tends to be the biggest indicator of the price of an Airbnb rental.
